In [2]:
def graph_g(k,p):  # define the name of function
  clique = nx.caveman_graph(1, k) # Returns a caveman graph of l cliques of size k
  ring = nx.cycle_graph(p)       # returns a cycle graph for ring shape of size p
  g = nx.union(clique,ring, rename=('clique-', 'ring-'))  # join both graph and rename each graph
  g.add_edge('clique-0', 'ring-0')                        # add an edge between both graph
  return g
In [3]:
g = graph_g(6,6)                     # create an example graph using k = 6 and p = 6 
nx.draw_networkx(g,with_labels=False)

BFS and DFS¶

In [13]:
# Breadth First Search
def bfs(graph):
  return list(nx.bfs_edges(g, source=list(g.nodes)[0])) #list(graph.nodes)[0] gives node with index 0

#Depth First Search
def dfs(graph):
  return list(nx.dfs_edges(graph, source=list(graph.nodes)[0]))   #list(graph.nodes)[0] gives node with index 0

from keras.applications.imagenet_utils import decode_predictions
from keras.applications import inception_v3
from keras.preprocessing.image import load_img
from keras.preprocessing.image import img_to_array
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.pyplot import imshow
import numpy as np
import math
import glob
from PIL import Image
imodel = inception_v3.InceptionV3(weights='imagenet')

tags ={}
for i, image in enumerate(images):
  im=load_img(image, target_size=(299, 299))
  numpy_image = img_to_array(im)
  image_batch = np.expand_dims(numpy_image, axis=0)
  processed_image = inception_v3.preprocess_input(image_batch.copy())
  predictions = imodel.predict(processed_image)
  label = decode_predictions(predictions)
  tags[image]=label
tags

significative_words ={}
for key, values in tags.items():       #iterate over tags dictionary
  significative_word = values[0][0]      # extract the tag with highest probability
  print(key+": "+significative_word[1])  # print the value
  significative_words[key] = significative_word[1] # append in the list for future use
